VALUES
(20, 10, 10, 10, 'kjv', 'He that winketh with the eye causeth sorrow:', 0, 44, 'question', 'Nature of Deceptive Actions', 'What does it mean for a person to wink with the eye in the context of relationships and trust? How do such seemingly minor actions contribute to greater sorrow or conflict in our lives and communities?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 10, 10, 'kjv', 'but a prating fool shall fall.', 45, 75, 'greek', 'Understanding ''prating''', 'μωρός (mōros, G3474) - foolish, dull, stupid. This term describes a person lacking in wisdom or good judgment. The use of this word emphasizes the serious nature of foolishness, suggesting that it not only leads to personal downfall but can also negatively impact those around them.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G3474", "description": "Strong''s number for the Greek term describing foolishness."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 11, 11, 'kjv', 'The mouth of a righteous man is a well of life', 0, 46, 'connection', 'Source of Life', 'This phrase can be connected to John 7:38, where Jesus speaks of believers having ''rivers of living water'' flowing from them. Both verses highlight the life-giving nature of divine wisdom and righteousness, suggesting that the words of the righteous not only reflect their character but also nourish others spiritually.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "John 7:38", "description": "Jesus'' teaching on the life-giving qualities of those who believe in Him."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 11, 11, 'kjv', 'violence covereth the mouth of the wicked', 52, 93, 'theology', 'Consequences of Wickedness', 'Many scholars believe that the ''violence'' mentioned here symbolizes the destructive nature of wicked speech and actions. This aligns with the broader biblical theme that emphasizes how sin can corrupt one’s ability to communicate truth and life. The mouth of the wicked becomes a source of harm rather than healing, illustrating the moral consequences of one''s choices.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 11, 11, 'kjv', 'The mouth of a righteous man is a well of life', 0, 46, 'question', 'What is True Righteousness?', 'How does understanding the mouth of a righteous man as a ''well of life'' challenge your perception of righteous living? In what ways can your words serve as a source of life for those around you, reflecting the wisdom and love of God?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 12, 12, 'kjv', 'Hatred stirreth up strifes: but love covereth all sins.', 0, 55, 'connection', 'Cross-Reference to James', 'James 1:20 states, ''For the anger of man does not produce the righteousness of God.'' This connection emphasizes the destructive nature of hatred and anger, reinforcing the idea that such emotions lead to conflict rather than resolution. Furthermore, Romans 13:10 declares, ''Love does no harm to a neighbor. Therefore love is the fulfillment of the law,'' highlighting love''s power to prevent strife and promote harmony.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "James 1:20", "description": "Highlights the futility of anger in achieving righteousness."}, {"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Romans 13:10", "description": "Affirms love as the antidote to conflict."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 12, 12, 'kjv', 'but love covereth all sins.', 28, 55, 'theology', 'The Nature of Love', 'Many scholars believe this passage reflects the Christian doctrine of forgiveness and reconciliation. Love, as described in this verse, is not merely an emotion but an active choice to overlook faults and foster unity. This aligns with 1 Peter 4:8, which states, ''Above all, love each other deeply, because love covers over a multitude of sins.'' Such teachings underscore the transformative power of love in community and personal relationships.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "1 Peter 4:8", "description": "Supports the idea of love''s redemptive qualities."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 12, 12, 'kjv', 'Hatred stirreth up strifes:', 0, 27, 'question', 'Reflection on Hatred', 'What specific situations in your life may be fueled by hatred or unresolved conflict? In what ways can you choose love to cover those situations instead? This verse challenges us to examine our hearts and relationships, prompting us to consider how we can actively pursue peace over strife.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'In the lips of him that hath understanding wisdom is found', 0, 58, 'connection', 'Wisdom''s Presence', 'This phrase connects to James 1:5, which encourages believers to seek wisdom from God. Both verses highlight that true understanding and wisdom are gifts that can be found through divine guidance. In the context of Proverbs, this reinforces the idea that wisdom is not merely intellectual but deeply spiritual and relational, intended to be sought and cherished.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "James 1:5", "description": "Encouragement to seek wisdom from God."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'but a rod is for the back of him that is void of understanding', 60, 122, 'theology', 'Discipline and Understanding', 'Many scholars believe this passage speaks to the necessity of discipline in the life of a believer. The ''rod'' symbolizes correction and guidance, suggesting that those lacking understanding may require more stringent forms of instruction. This aligns with Hebrews 12:6, which states that the Lord disciplines those He loves, emphasizing the importance of receiving correction as a means of spiritual growth.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Hebrews 12:6", "description": "The Lord''s discipline as a sign of love."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'In the lips of him that hath understanding wisdom is found', 0, 58, 'question', 'Understanding and Wisdom', 'What does it mean for wisdom to be found in the lips of those who have understanding? How does this challenge your own communication and decision-making? Consider how your words reflect your understanding of God’s truth and the wisdom He provides.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'but a rod is for the back of him that is void of understanding', 60, 122, 'greek', 'Understanding in Greek', 'אֱנוֹשׁ (enosh, H582) - man, mortal. This term underlines the frailty of humanity without divine wisdom. It highlights that lacking understanding is a common human condition requiring God’s guidance and correction.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H582", "description": "Strong''s number for the term ''enosh''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'Wise men lay up knowledge', 0, 25, 'connection', 'Wisdom and Knowledge', 'This phrase echoes Proverbs 1:7, which states, ''The fear of the Lord is the beginning of knowledge.'' Both verses highlight the importance of acquiring wisdom as a foundational aspect of life. Understanding and knowledge are not just intellectual pursuits; they are rooted in reverence for God. This connection underscores how true wisdom is linked to spiritual awareness and relationship with God.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Proverbs 1:7", "description": "Highlights the foundational aspect of wisdom in relation to God''s fear."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'the mouth of the foolish is near destruction', 31, 75, 'theology', 'Consequences of Foolishness', 'Many scholars believe this passage illustrates the broader theological theme of accountability in speech. The mouth, as a source of both wisdom and foolishness, reflects one''s inner state and relationship with God. Proverbs often warns that foolish talk leads to ruin, aligning with James 3:6, which states that the tongue can set a great fire. This serves as a reminder of the power of words and the moral responsibility that comes with them.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "James 3:6", "description": "Emphasizes the destructive potential of careless speech."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'Wise men lay up knowledge', 0, 25, 'question', 'Value of Knowledge', 'What does it mean for you personally to ''lay up knowledge''? In what ways can you actively pursue wisdom that aligns with God''s truth in your daily life? Reflect on practical steps you can take to deepen your understanding and application of biblical wisdom.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'the mouth of the foolish is near destruction', 31, 75, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Destruction''', 'ἀπώλεια (apoleia, G684) - destruction, loss, waste. This term emphasizes not only physical destruction but also spiritual and relational loss. In the context of this verse, it signifies the dire consequences that follow foolish words, which can lead to the downfall of relationships and one''s own spiritual state.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G684", "description": "Strong''s number for the Greek term related to destruction."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'The rich man’s wealth is his strong city', 0, 40, 'connection', 'Wealth as Security', 'This phrase connects to Proverbs 18:11, which states, ''The rich man''s wealth is his strong city, and like a high wall in his own imagination.'' This highlights the false sense of security wealth can provide, suggesting that while it may offer temporary safety, it can also lead to pride and complacency. The comparison emphasizes that true security should not rest solely on material possessions.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Proverbs 18:11", "description": "Connects the idea of wealth providing a false sense of security."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'the destruction of the poor is their poverty', 42, 86, 'theology', 'Poverty and Destruction', 'This passage suggests a theological reflection on the nature of poverty and its impact on the human condition. Many scholars believe that poverty is not merely a lack of resources but a state that can lead to moral and social degradation. The Bible often portrays poverty as a challenge that requires compassion and justice from the community, highlighting God''s concern for the marginalized.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'The rich man’s wealth is his strong city', 0, 40, 'greek', 'City Imagery', 'πόλις (polis, G4172) - city, community, body of citizens. The use of ''strong city'' evokes imagery of safety and societal structure, suggesting that wealth creates a fortified existence. This underscores the idea that one''s sense of security and identity can be wrapped in material possessions, which may distract from spiritual truths.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G4172", "description": "Strong''s number for the Greek term for city."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'the destruction of the poor is their poverty', 42, 86, 'question', 'Reflecting on Poverty', 'In what ways does this verse challenge your understanding of wealth and poverty? How can recognizing poverty as a state of destruction motivate you to engage more compassionately with those in need?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'The labour of the righteous tendeth to life', 0, 43, 'connection', 'Righteousness and Life', 'This phrase resonates with Romans 6:22, which states that being freed from sin and becoming servants of God leads to sanctification and eternal life. The connection underscores the biblical principle that righteous living results in life, both spiritually and physically. This highlights the transformative aspect of righteousness as foundational to a life aligned with God''s purposes.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Romans 6:22", "description": "This verse connects righteous living with the promise of eternal life."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'the fruit of the wicked to sin', 45, 75, 'theology', 'Consequences of Wickedness', 'Many scholars believe this reflects the biblical doctrine of sowing and reaping, as seen in Galatians 6:7-8. The passage suggests that wicked actions yield sinful outcomes, emphasizing the moral order established by God. This reinforces the idea that one''s choices have consequences that align with divine justice, pointing to the necessity of righteousness in life.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Galatians 6:7-8", "description": "This verse illustrates the principle of reaping what one sows."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'The labour of the righteous tendeth to life', 0, 43, 'question', 'Understanding Righteous Labour', 'What does it mean for the labour of the righteous to lead to life, and how can we apply this truth in our daily work? Consider how our efforts, when aligned with God''s will, contribute not only to our own flourishing but also to the well-being of others in our communities.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'He is in the way of life that keepeth instruction', 0, 49, 'connection', 'Instruction and Wisdom', 'This phrase connects to Psalm 119:105, which states, ''Thy word is a lamp unto my feet, and a light unto my path.'' Both verses emphasize the importance of guidance and instruction in living a life aligned with God''s will. Keeping instruction is not just about knowledge; it''s about applying that knowledge to navigate life''s challenges wisely.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 119:105", "description": "Emphasizes the guiding nature of God''s word."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'but he that refuseth reproof erreth', 51, 86, 'theology', 'Value of Reproof', 'Many scholars believe that this verse underscores the theological concept of humility in receiving correction. Proverbs often highlights the wise person''s openness to reproof as a pathway to growth and understanding. This reflects the broader biblical teaching that God disciplines those He loves (Hebrews 12:6), indicating that reproof is an integral part of spiritual maturity.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Hebrews 12:6", "description": "Discusses God''s discipline as an expression of love."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'He is in the way of life that keepeth instruction', 0, 49, 'question', 'Following Instruction', 'What does it mean to truly ''keep'' instruction in your daily life? How can you actively apply the teachings of Scripture to ensure you are on the ''way of life''?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'He that hideth hatred with lying lips', 0, 37, 'connection', 'Hidden Hatred in Scripture', 'This phrase resonates with 1 John 2:9, which states, ''He who says he is in the light, and hates his brother, is in darkness until now.'' Both verses highlight the danger of concealing hatred, emphasizing the contrast between outward appearances and inner realities. This connection underscores the importance of authenticity in relationships and the perils of hypocrisy.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "1 John 2:9", "description": "Highlights the theme of hidden hatred."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'and he that uttereth a slander', 39, 69, 'theology', 'The Nature of Slander', 'Many scholars believe that slander is not just a social wrong but also a spiritual issue, reflecting a heart disconnected from God''s truth. Slander violates the commandment to love one''s neighbor and reveals the deeper issues of pride and insecurity in the heart. This passage suggests that our words hold significant power and responsibility in our moral and spiritual lives.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'is a fool.', 71, 81, 'question', 'Understanding Foolishness', 'What does it mean to be labeled a fool in the context of this verse? How does this challenge your understanding of wisdom versus foolishness? Consider the implications of choosing deceit over honesty and how this affects your relationships and spiritual life.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'He that hideth hatred with lying lips', 0, 37, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Lying Lips''', 'שקר (sheqer, H8267) - falsehood, deceit. This Hebrew term emphasizes the destructive nature of lies, showcasing that false speech is not merely a social faux pas but a moral failing. In this context, lying lips signify a deeper betrayal of trust and integrity, reinforcing the idea that truthfulness is essential in our speech.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H8267", "description": "Highlights the meaning of deceit in the verse."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'In the multitude of words there wanteth not sin', 0, 47, 'connection', 'Excessive Speech Warning', 'This phrase resonates with James 1:19, which advises being ''quick to hear, slow to speak, slow to anger.'' Both verses highlight the dangers of excessive speech, suggesting that many words can lead to sin, miscommunication, or conflict. This connection emphasizes the importance of thoughtful speech in maintaining wisdom and righteousness.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "James 1:19", "description": "Encouragement to be cautious with words"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'but he that refraineth his lips is wise', 49, 88, 'theology', 'Wisdom in Restraint', 'Many scholars believe that the ability to refrain from speaking unnecessarily is a key aspect of biblical wisdom. This aligns with the concept of self-control, a fruit of the Spirit as noted in Galatians 5:22-23. Theologically, wisdom is not merely intellectual but is deeply connected to moral behavior, suggesting that true wisdom involves knowing when to speak and when to listen.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Galatians 5:22-23", "description": "Fruit of the Spirit includes self-control"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'In the multitude of words there wanteth not sin', 0, 47, 'question', 'Reflection on Speech', 'What does it mean for our conversations and interactions if many words can lead to sin? How can we practice restraint in our speech to align more closely with the wisdom described in this proverb?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'The tongue of the just is as choice silver', 0, 42, 'connection', 'Value of Speech', 'This phrase resonates with Psalm 12:6, which states, ''The words of the Lord are pure words, like silver tried in a furnace of earth, purified seven times.'' Both verses highlight the intrinsic value and purity of righteous speech, suggesting that just words are as precious and refined as silver. This connection emphasizes the importance of speaking truthfully and wisely.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 12:6", "description": "Highlights the purity and value of truthful speech."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'the heart of the wicked is little worth', 44, 83, 'theology', 'Heart''s Condition', 'This passage suggests that the value of one''s heart is intrinsically linked to one''s moral and ethical choices. Many scholars believe that this reflects the biblical teaching that true worth is measured not by external appearances or possessions but by one''s character and intentions. This aligns with Matthew 15:18, where Jesus teaches that what comes out of the mouth reflects the heart''s condition.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew 15:18", "description": "Connects heart condition with speech and actions."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'The tongue of the just is as choice silver', 0, 42, 'question', 'Value of Our Words', 'In what ways can we ensure that our speech reflects the value of ''choice silver''? How does the quality of our conversations influence our witness to others and our relationship with God?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'The lips of the righteous feed many', 0, 35, 'connection', 'Righteous Speech in Scripture', 'This phrase connects well with Matthew 12:34 where Jesus teaches that ''out of the abundance of the heart the mouth speaks.'' The righteous, filled with wisdom and goodness, naturally share life-giving words that nourish others spiritually. This highlights the importance of internal righteousness manifesting in our speech.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Matthew 12:34", "description": "Jesus emphasizes the connection between heart and speech."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'but fools die for want of wisdom', 37, 69, 'theology', 'Consequences of Foolishness', 'Many scholars believe that this passage illustrates the peril of disregarding wisdom, a central theme in Proverbs. The ''fools'' represent those who reject divine guidance, leading not only to spiritual death but also to a lack of fulfillment in life. This aligns with the overarching biblical principle that true life is found in following God’s wisdom.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Proverbs 1:7", "description": "The fear of the Lord is the beginning of knowledge."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'The lips of the righteous feed many', 0, 35, 'question', 'Impact of Our Words', 'In what ways can your words nourish those around you? Reflect on how your speech can either uplift or harm others, and consider practical steps to ensure your communication reflects righteousness and wisdom.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'but fools die for want of wisdom', 37, 69, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Wisdom''', 'חָכְמָה (chokmah, H2451) - wisdom, skill, intelligence. This term emphasizes not just knowledge but the application of understanding in practical life. The absence of such wisdom can lead to dire consequences, as suggested in this verse.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H2451", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word for wisdom."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'The blessing of the Lord, it maketh rich, and he addeth no sorrow with it.', 0, 74, 'connection', 'Cross-Reference to Wealth', 'This verse connects with Deuteronomy 8:18, which states, ''But you shall remember the Lord your God, for it is he who gives you power to get wealth.'' Both passages emphasize that true wealth comes from God''s blessing and underscores the importance of recognizing Him as the source. This connection enriches our understanding of divine provision as devoid of regret or sorrow.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Deuteronomy 8:18", "description": "Emphasizes God''s role in providing wealth."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'maketh rich', 29, 40, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Rich''', 'עָשָׁר (ashar, H6238) - to be rich, wealthy. This Hebrew term implies not just material wealth but also a state of well-being and fullness. The richness bestowed by God encompasses spiritual, emotional, and physical abundance, suggesting a holistic view of prosperity that aligns with God''s intentions for His people.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H6238", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word ''ashar''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'no sorrow with it.', 56, 74, 'theology', 'Nature of Divine Blessing', 'Many scholars believe that the absence of sorrow in God''s blessings points to His perfect gifts, as seen in James 1:17, which states that every good and perfect gift comes from above. This suggests that God''s blessings are not only abundant but also free from the burdens that often accompany worldly riches, reflecting His love and care for His people.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "James 1:17", "description": "Affirms the goodness of God''s gifts."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'The blessing of the Lord', 0, 24, 'question', 'Source of True Blessing', 'What does it mean for you personally to perceive the blessings in your life as coming from the Lord? In what ways can recognizing this source transform your understanding of material wealth versus spiritual richness?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'It is as sport to a fool to do mischief:', 0, 40, 'connection', 'Fools and Mischief', 'This phrase echoes Ecclesiastes 10:13 which states, ''The beginning of the words of his mouth is foolishness: and the end of his talk is mischievous madness.'' Both passages highlight the destructive nature of a fool''s actions, pointing to the folly in taking pleasure in wrongdoing. Such connections emphasize the biblical view of wisdom versus folly.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Ecclesiastes 10:13", "description": "Highlights the destructive nature of foolish talk and actions."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'but a man of understanding hath wisdom.', 41, 80, 'theology', 'Understanding and Wisdom', 'This passage suggests that true wisdom is intrinsically linked to understanding, a core principle in biblical theology. Many scholars believe that understanding involves not just knowledge, but the application of that knowledge in a way that honors God. This aligns with James 1:5, which encourages believers to seek wisdom from God.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'It is as sport to a fool to do mischief:', 0, 40, 'question', 'Nature of Sinful Pleasure', 'What does it reveal about human nature that some find enjoyment in mischief? How can this understanding shape our response to sinful tendencies in ourselves and others?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'but a man of understanding hath wisdom.', 41, 80, 'greek', 'Wisdom in Greek', 'σοφία (sophia, G4678) - wisdom, insight, skill. This term captures not just intellectual knowledge, but also the practical application of that knowledge in daily life, reinforcing the idea that wisdom is a lived experience rather than mere theoretical knowledge.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G4678", "description": "Strong''s definition of the term for wisdom."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'The fear of the wicked, it shall come upon him:', 0, 47, 'connection', 'Fear and Consequence', 'This phrase connects with Job 18:14, which states, ''His confidence is rooted in the dust, and his trust is a spider''s web.'' Both passages emphasize the inevitable consequences faced by the wicked due to their fears. This connection highlights a biblical theme where one''s actions lead directly to their fate, reinforcing the moral order established by God.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Job 18:14", "description": "Job reflects on the fate of the wicked, similar to Proverbs 10:24."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'but the desire of the righteous shall be granted.', 48, 97, 'theology', 'Desire of the Righteous', 'Many scholars believe this verse encapsulates a core theological truth about divine justice, suggesting that God desires to fulfill the aspirations of the righteous. This aligns with Psalm 37:4, which states, ''Delight yourself in the LORD, and he will give you the desires of your heart.'' This encourages believers to cultivate righteousness, trusting in God''s provision.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 37:4", "description": "Psalm highlights God''s promise to fulfill the desires of those who seek Him."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini');